81. 19. Quae . . . . abhorreret. Melmoth thinks that Cicero refers in this passage to a custom which prevailed in Rome, by which the general, whose arms had made any new acquisition of territory to the republic, was the declared patron of those people whom he had subdued. These were afterwards considered as the hereditary clients of his family, to the head of which they constantly had recourse, as their standing advocate, in all those causes of a na- tional concern which they had occasion to plead
